# AI Content Factory

## Purpose

Autonomous short-form video production for YouTube (Phase 1), with multi-platform publishing planned (TikTok, Instagram Reels). Production is platform-agnostic; upload lives in `publishers/`.

## Architecture

```
core/          → agents, images, TTS, render, DB (no platform knowledge)
publishers/    → upload adapters (youtube first, then tiktok, instagram)
prompts/       → LLM system prompts; outputs must be valid JSON only
config/        → channel identity (niche, tone, format, duration)
data/          → SQLite and runtime state
assets/        → ephemeral scene images, voice, temp files
output/        → final videos and content packages (gitignored)
```

## Phase 1 stack

| Layer | Tool |
|-------|------|
| LLM | Gemini API |
| Stock visuals | Pexels API |
| AI visuals | Pollinations (HTTP) |
| Voice | edge-tts (Turkish) |
| Render | FFmpeg (9:16 Shorts) |
| Upload | YouTube Data API v3 |
| Storage | SQLite |
| Scheduling | Windows Task Scheduler (n8n in Phase 2 only) |

## Code standards

- Minimal, focused diffs; match existing patterns
- Never commit secrets: `.env`, `credentials/`, `token.json`
- Every successful run produces `content_package.json` + `video.mp4`
- No render or upload without Reviewer `APPROVE`
- Default format: Shorts, 9:16, ~45–60 seconds
- `publishers/base.py` interface for future platforms; do not hardcode YouTube in `core/`

## Agent pipeline

1. Topic Agent → unique topic (respect `used_topics`)
2. Master Content Agent → full production JSON
3. Reviewer Agent → quality gate (avg ≥ 7, policy_risk ≥ 7)
4. On REJECT: retry Master with `fix_instructions` (max 2 attempts)

## User workflow

- User progresses step-by-step and commits manually
- Agent suggests commit messages only; no automatic commit or push
- Missing API keys or accounts: explain setup steps to the user before proceeding

## n8n

- Not used in Phase 1
- Phase 2: orchestration only (cron → HTTP trigger → notify); render stays in Python
